[{"id":"VR797925","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A solid, charged, insulating sphere of radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase R\"><math alttext=\"uppercase R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span> has a spherically symmetric charge distribution that varies as a function of the distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase r\"><math alttext=\"lowercase r\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>r</mi></math></span></span> from the sphere’s center. The charge density within the sphere is given by <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"rho of lowercase r equals, beta times lowercase r\"><math alttext=\"rho of lowercase r equals, beta times lowercase r\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>ρ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>β</mi><mi>r</mi></math></span></span>, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"beta\"><math alttext=\"beta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>β</mi></math></span></span> is a constant with appropriate units. What is the magnitude of the electric field at a point inside the sphere at a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase R over 2\"><math alttext=\"uppercase R over 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></span></span> from the center of the sphere?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR797925_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction with numerator beta times uppercase R squared, and denominator 64 times epsilon sub 0\"><math alttext=\"the fraction with numerator beta times uppercase R squared, and denominator 64 times epsilon sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>β</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>64</mn><msub><mi>ε</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></m